# Module 13: Loops

A loop repeats commands.

## `for` loop

Use when values or repetitions are known.

```bash
for i in {1..5}
## `while` loop
Runs while a condition is true.

```bash
COUNT=1

while [ "$COUNT" -le 5 ]
do
    echo "$COUNT"
    COUNT=$((COUNT + 1))
    done
## `until` loop
Runs while the condition is false and stops when it becomes true.
## Difference

| Loop    | Use                                   |
| ------- | ------------------------------------- |
| `for`   | Known list or number of repetitions   |
| `while` | Continue while condition is true      |
| `until` | Continue until condition becomes true |

---

## `break`

Stops the loop immediately.

```bash
for i in {1..10}
do
    if [ "$i" -eq 5 ]
    then
        break
    fi

    echo "$i"
done

## `continue`

Skips only the current repetition.

```bash
for i in {1..5}
do
    if [ "$i" -eq 3 ]
    then
        continue
    fi

    echo "$i"
done
