# Module 19: Signals

A signal is a message sent to a running process.

Signals can tell a process to:

* Stop
* Terminate
* Pause
* Continue

Common signals:

| Signal    | Number | Purpose                            |
| --------- | -----: | ---------------------------------- |
| `SIGINT`  |      2 | Interrupt; commonly sent by Ctrl+C |
| `SIGKILL` |      9 | Forcefully terminate               |
| `SIGTERM` |     15 | Request graceful termination       |
| `SIGCONT` |     18 | Continue a paused process          |
| `SIGSTOP` |     19 | Pause a process                    |

---

## `SIGTERM`

```bash
kill PID
```

or:

```bash
kill -15 PID
```

Requests the program to stop gracefully.

---

## `SIGKILL`

```bash
kill -9 PID
```

Forcefully stops the process.

Use it only when normal termination does not work.

---

## Interview difference

| SIGTERM                      | SIGKILL                            |
| ---------------------------- | ---------------------------------- |
| Graceful termination request | Immediate forced termination       |
| Signal 15                    | Signal 9                           |
| Program may clean up         | Program cannot handle or ignore it |

